The application provides a forgot password functionality that sends a password reset link to the registered email address. Upon accessing the reset link, the application prompts for an email address and a new password.

It was observed that while attempting to change the password for another user by modifying the email address results in an invalid request error, the functionality allows submission of arbitrary email addresses along with new passwords. By repeatedly submitting requests with a target user’s email and different passwords, the application returns a distinct response when a previously used password is entered (e.g., “cannot reuse password”).

This behavior enables an attacker to brute-force or enumerate previously used passwords for other users based on the variation in server responses.


Navigate to the application and initiate the Forgot Password functionality using a valid account.
Open the password reset link received in the email.
Observe that the application prompts for email address and new password.
In the email field, enter a different (target) user’s email address.
Submit the request with a random new password and observe the response (e.g., invalid request/error).
Repeat the request multiple times with the same target email but different passwords.
Provide a password that is known or likely to have been previously used by the target user.
Observe that the application returns a different response (e.g., “cannot reuse password”), indicating password reuse detection.
